<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-731-124  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 731 124.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Oct 2 1989 v8 n20 p86(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Conflict of interest can have a serious result for a buy.andO;(Fedwatch.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dornan, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Conflict of InterestPurchasing SystemsEthicsLegal IssuesGovernment Contracts.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Conflict of Interest Can Have Serious Result for a BuyandM;Procurement integrity continues to raise eyebrows in Washington.andP;  Industryand agency officials alike must be very careful about real or apparentconflicts of interest.andP;  Violations can result in substantial criminal andcontractual penalties.andM;In protest 10031-P, dated July 25, 1989, the General Services AdministrationBoard of Contract Appeals terminated an Energy Department contract with U.S.andO;West Inc., Englewood, Colo., because of a conflict of interest, among otherthings.andM;Westinghouse Electric Corp., Pittsburgh, acting as Energy's procuring agent,selected U.S.andP;  West for the contract award.andM;Before the award, United Telephone protested.andP;  United alleged that a U.S.andO;West subcontractor, Science and Engineering Associates Inc., Seattle, hired aformer top Energy official.andP;  This person was primarily responsible fordeveloping the request for proposals for the contract.andP;  After retirement,this person worked for SEA and participated extensively in the procurement.andO;He represented the bidding team at several meetings.andM;GSBCA said a &quot;preponderance of evidence&quot; standard governs civil proceedings,including protests.andP;  By this standard, U.S.andP;  West violated the conflict ofinterest regulations.andP;  As a result, the GSBCA directed Energy to award thecontract to United, the second ranked offerer.andM;There is a key lesson in this protest.andP;  Vendors should not employ formergovernment officials and then allow them actively to represent the company ina conflict of interest.andP;  Just as important, companies must ensure thatsubcontractors adhere to the rules.andM;Be forewarned that this kind of allegation is easier to prove in a protestproceeding where the &quot;preponderance of evidence&quot; standard is used.andP;  Criminalproceedings use tougher standards.andM;Bob Dornan is vice president of Federal Sources Inc., Vienna, Va.andO;</TEXT></DOC>